a NIL program executes as a process.
A Process corresponds to a single agent within the context of the host system.
A Process will have permission to access some resources and may not have
permission to access other resources.

A Process may include one more more threads which are sub-processes which will
have access to the data contained by that Process and will also share the
same permissions and statuses that the host has afforded the Process.

A thread may create additional data which is local to itself.
Threads do not have access to local data which it did not create.


A Process may have access to data and resources which are global to the host.
Some common examples include, the filesystem, network capabilities, and
environment values.

NIL provides portable access to these resources if they are available in a host.

Specifically NIL provides access to the filessystem, the network stack, and
the environment, and the ability to directly call routines provided by the host.

